Resolved:
The Postgres init script (db-init/postgres/01-create-databases.sh, run by the postgres image's docker-entrypoint-initdb.d mechanism) called `psql` without `--dbname`. psql's undocumented-feeling default in that case isn't POSTGRES_DB — it's a database named after the connecting user. That database (kotlincrud) stopped existing the moment POSTGRES_DB was changed from kotlincrud to identity, so the script failed with "database kotlincrud does not exist" and the `orders` database was silently never created. Fixed by passing `--dbname postgres` explicitly (the maintenance database that's always present), so the script no longer depends on what POSTGRES_DB happens to be set to. General lesson: any script invoking psql should always pass `--dbname`/`-d` explicitly — never rely on its default.

The Mongo init script (db-init/mongo/01-create-databases.js, mongosh) referenced a just-created collection via `db._bootstrap`, which evaluated to `undefined` instead of the Collection object — mongosh's Database object already carries its own internal properties prefixed with an underscore, and those shadow the dynamic collection-name property accessor for any collection whose name also starts with `_`. This crashed the container on first run with "TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'insertOne')". Fixed with the explicit `db.getCollection('_bootstrap')` accessor, which isn't subject to the shadowing. General lesson: don't rely on mongosh's dot-notation collection access for names that could collide with the Database object's own properties (anything underscore-prefixed in particular) — use `getCollection()`.

Both were only caught by actually running the containers end-to-end and inspecting the resulting databases — the scripts read as correct.
